column4: I want to feel more confident and prepared in advisor meetings.
column5: I often feel nervous and forget to ask questions or explain things clearly.
column6: ['Write 3 main updates and questions before meetings', 'Bring a visual summary of key points', 'Start the meeting with a clear agenda', 'Practice updates out loud beforehand', 'Take notes on what feedback I get']
column7: ['Pay attention to where my advisor seems confused', 'Notice when I rush or lose focus', 'Watch for nonverbal cues like nodding or frowning', "Track whether I'm listening or zoning out", 'Notice how I respond under pressure']
column8: ['Advisor wants me to lead the meeting, not just report', "Short replies don't mean disapproval", 'Constructive feedback means engagement', "Feeling nervous doesn't mean I'm unprepared", "It's okay to ask again if I don't understand"]
column9: ['Take a breath if I feel overwhelmed', 'Speak clearly even if unsure', 'Ask questions without overthinking', 'Keep a calm, open body posture', 'Pause instead of rushing to respond']

column51: ['I scheduled a meeting with my advisor to share updates when I felt more prepared.', 'I politely greeted my advisor but said I would email her later with a full update.', 'I ran into my advisor unexpectedly but chose to listen and ask about her work first.', 'I ran into my advisor but suggested grabbing coffee later to chat when we both had more time.', 'I ran into my advisor and asked if she had a few minutes to hear a quick update on my progress.']
column52: ['I gave a concise overview and said I would follow up with more details via email.', 'I asked if we could step into her office for a few minutes to minimize distractions.', 'I pulled out my notebook to reference my main points while giving the summary.', 'I gave a high-level summary and asked when would be a good time to review in more depth.', 'I briefly shared my progress and asked for her initial thoughts and guidance.']
column53: ['I focused on her constructive feedback and appreciated her taking the time to listen.', 'I noted her suggestions and shifted focus to asking about her recent work.', 'I thanked her for the feedback and changed the subject to the nice weather outside.', 'I redirected my attention to the parts she said were going well to boost my confidence.', 'I focused on the value of her input rather than fixating on her distracted demeanor.']
column54: ['I reframed it as an opportunity to improve my work with her expert guidance.', 'I recognized she likely had a lot on her mind and her feedback was still valuable.', 'I viewed it as a chance to practice impromptu presenting and get better over time.', 'I reminded myself that advisors are busy and her feedback showed she did listen.', 'I reinterpreted her reaction as indicating areas I could strengthen, not failure.']
column55: ['I took some deep breaths to calm down and looked over the notes to plan improvements.', 'I went for a short walk to clear my head before coming back to process the feedback.', 'I acknowledged feeling embarrassed to a friend and asked them to help me stay motivated.', 'I reread the positive parts of her feedback to balance out my embarrassment.', 'I decided to tackle the easiest point first to build momentum and dissolve my embarrassment.']
